# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australian-rules-football-in-australia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] The **1970 VFL Grand Final** was an Australian rules football game contested between the Carlton Football Club and Collingwood Football Club, held at the Melbourne Cricket Ground (MCG) on 26 September 1970.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] It was the 73rd annual Grand Final of the Victorian Football League, staged to determine the premiers for the 1970 VFL season.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] The match was won by Carlton who came back from a 44-point deficit at halftime to win by a margin of 10 points, marking that club's 10th premiership victory.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] This game is widely considered to be one of the greatest Grand Finals of all time and, according to one of the key protagonists Ted Hopkins, heralded "the birth of modern football".
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] The attendance figure of 121,696 spectators broke the grand final record set the previous year of 119,165 spectators, and set an all-time attendance record for any football code in Australia that still stands.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Collingwood finished 1970 on top of the ladder with 18 wins.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Carlton was next with 16 wins, followed by St Kilda and South Melbourne (14 wins each).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] South Melbourne was participating in its first Finals series since 1945, and got in despite winning only four of their last eight home-and-away matches.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] During the home-and-away season, Collingwood and Carlton had played each other twice.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] In Round 8 at VFL Park, Carlton had led by 29 points at half-time before being overrun to lose by 23.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] In the return fixture at Victoria Park in Round 19, Collingwood thrashed Carlton by 77 points, at the time the club's greatest winning margin against Carlton.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] The two clubs faced each other again in the Second Semi-final, which was a closely fought battle won by Collingwood 17.16 (118) d.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Carlton qualified for the grand final with a comfortable 62-point victory against St Kilda in the preliminary final.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Collingwood had last played in a VFL Grand Final in 1966, which was won by St Kilda by one point, while the Blues were playing in their third consecutive VFL Grand Final.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] The match was the fourth grand final between the two traditional rivals, the previous occurring in 1910, 1915 and 1938.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Percy Beames, chief football writer for *The Age*, predicted a Collingwood win, along with four other colleagues, while three tipped a Carlton premiership, among them Geelong full-forward Doug Wade.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Collingwood named an unchanged line-up from the team that had defeated Carlton in the Second Semi-final.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] There had been some concern over star ruckman Len Thompson, who had not trained for the entire week leading up to the Grand Final on doctor's orders.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] The umpiring panel for the match, comprising one field umpire, two boundary umpires and two goal umpires is given below.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] The attendance of 121,696 spectators was the highest in the history of the league, a record still held today.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Carlton captain Nicholls won the toss and chose to kick toward the Punt Road End.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Kicking against a very slight breeze, Collingwood were into attack straight away when umpire Jolley awarded a free kick to ruckman Jenkin from the opening bounce.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] For the next 20 minutes, the Magpies midfielders continually won the ball and drove deep into the forward line with long kicks, while the Blues struggled to maintain any sort of meaningful possession.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Collingwood opened the scoring with behinds before former captain Tuddenham gathered the ball from a handpass under pressure from Max Richardson, evaded an attempted bump and snapped the first goal of the game at the 5-minute mark.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Star full-forward McKenna followed up with his first goal of the match at the 13-minute mark, converting a free kick set shot after great play upfield from O'Callaghan, Price and Tuddenham.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] After his snap shot hit the post earlier in the quarter, Britt received a handball from McKenna in the forward pocket to score Collingwood's third goal at the 23-minute mark.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Up to that stage, Carlton had yet to register a score, but the Magpies had not fully capitalized on their momentum, with their score only reading 3 goals 6 behinds (24 points).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] It took the Blues until the 23-minute mark of the quarter to register its first score, with a behind to Crosswell after bringing the ball forward through scrappy play.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] A minute later, Jesaulenko had a great chance to kick Carlton's first goal when he took a strong mark from a rushed kick forward by Silvagni, only to miss his set shot from directly in front.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Collingwood responded at the 29-minute mark when a pass from Wayne Richardson found McKenna, whose set shot from 20 yards out on a slight angle gave him his second goal for the game.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] The quarter-time siren sounded shortly afterward, with Collingwood 29 points ahead.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] The Blues finally scored their first goal of the game in the second minute of the quarter, when rover Gallagher converted his free kick set shot after a careless bump from Jenkin.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Collingwood responded almost immediately when McKenna got front position to a long kick into the forward line from Dean and marked strongly before kicking his third goal.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Then at the 8-minute mark, the Magpies scored two goals in quick succession; the first came when Clifton intercepted an attempted pass by Gallagher on Carlton's half-forward line and kicked long into attack.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Coming out from Collingwood's forward line to gather possession of the ball, Dunne grabbed it on the half volley, turned on to his non-preferred left foot and snapped a long-range goal.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Then from the subsequent centre bounce, Collingwood captain Waters sharked Jones' hit-out and sent another long kick into Collingwood's forward line.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] McKenna was in the right place to gather the bouncing ball and snap his fourth goal to extend Collingwood's lead to 44 points.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] As such, the half time margin remained 44 points.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Notable among the highlights in the quarter came in the 27th minute, when Jesaulenko (Carlton) leapt onto the shoulders of Collingwood ruckman Graeme Jenkin and took a spectacular mark that was judged the official 1970 Mark of the Year.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Mike Williamson's TV commentary of the mark, "Oh, Jesaulenko, you beauty!" has endured as famous as the mark itself, and was later included in the Toyota Legendary Moments series of advertisements.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Although the Magpies had built a formidable and seemingly insurmountable half-time lead, there was one incident that had fans worried; Collingwood's superstar full-forward McKenna was groggy after teammate Tuddenham had accidentally floored him with a hip-and-shoulder while flying for a chest mark.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] McKenna, who already had kicked over 140 goals for the season and five goals in the first half.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] He would only kick one more goal for the rest of the match.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] The fact that this goal came from an overhead mark only 2 minutes and 43 seconds after the collision caused the TV commentators to believe that he had recovered.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] During the break, champion Carlton coach Ron Barassi instructed his players to handball and play on at all costs, instituting a strategy to try to nullify Collingwood's long kicking game.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] A key positional move was the introduction of little-known Ted Hopkins, a small rover, as a substitute for Bert Thornley in the second half.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] These changes were highly effective and in the early part of the third quarter, Carlton staged one of the most remarkable purple patches in league history, kicking seven goals in eleven minutes to draw the margin back to only three points.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Substitute Ted Hopkins kicked the first two, roving the ball from broken marking contests in the goal square in the 3rd and 4th minutes of the quarter.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] In the 7th minute, Syd Jackson snapped a goal from near the boundary line in the forward pocket.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] In the 8th minute, Brent Crosswell kicked a goal from a high tackle free kick.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Hopkins kicked his third goal in the 10th minute after receiving a handpass from Robert Walls, who had marked at half-forward; and in the 12th minute, Walls marked at half forward again, this time playing on and kicking the goal himself.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Finally, in the 14th minute, from a ball-up in the forward pocket, Hopkins managed to kick the ball to Alex Jesaulenko who scored a goal to bring the margin back to only three points, 10.14 (74) vs 11.5 (71).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Thereafter, Collingwood steadied, and the second half of the third quarter was a much more even contest.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] In the 20th minute, Collingwood extended the lead to 10 points with a set shot goal by Len Thompson.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Two minutes later, Jesaulenko kicked a goal for Carlton from a free kick, and from the ensuing centre bounce, Collingwood responded with a goal to Ross Dunne from a close range mark.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] In the 28th minute, McKenna marked and kicked his sixth goal from 20m, and shortly before the three-quarter time siren he kicked another behind, to extend the margin to 17 points.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] At this point, Collingwood was 21 points ahead, having scored the last three goals.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Soon after, Carlton had three shots inside three minutes to narrow the margin back to eight points, largely through the efforts of ruckman John Nicholls who was resting forward.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] No goals were kicked in the following ten minutes, both teams' defences repeatedly repelling attacks.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Collingwood's 19th and 20th men were both brought on to replace cramping teammates.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] In the 20th minute, Syd Jackson made a brilliant piece of individual play, smothering then regathering an attempted clearing kick by Eakins, before handpassing to an unmarked Hopkins at full forward, who kicked his fourth goal and brought the margin back to one point.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] As time-on neared, Crosswell was awarded a free kick for a high tackle from Tuddenham and took his set shot on an angle from 35 metres out.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] In an interview for the *AFL Record* 50 years later, Crosswell recalled that “the wind was going slightly right to left and I remember thinking I needed to kick it towards the right goalpost.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] The Blues had taken the lead for the first time in the match, amidst scenes of pandemonium in the stands.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] At this point, Carlton had kicked the last 5.2 (32) of the game.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Dunne kicked a behind for Collingwood in the 29th minute to narrow the margin to ten points, and the siren went shortly after.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] This was the same winning margin as the Second Semi Final also played at the MCG two weeks earlier between these teams which Collingwood won 17.16 (118) to 17.6 (108).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Leading ball winners for Carlton were Crosswell with 23 (17 kicks and 6 handballs), McKay 20 (18 and 2) and Waite 19 (10 and 9).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] For Collingwood, Price 22 (17 and 5), W.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Richardson 19 (13 and 6) Brent Crosswell (Carlton) was generally regarded as the best player on the day for his four-quarter contribution, especially in the first half when many Carlton players were not playing well.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Hopkins, whose four goals as 19th man became legendary, played only one further game for Carlton, soon quitting football to pursue other interests.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] The game was immediately hailed across the Australian sporting press as an all-time classic.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] He also wrote that the Collingwood players had little excuse for letting down their coach Bob Rose, compared to their losses in 1964 and 1966.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Besides their scoring inaccuracy, Beames also criticised Collingwood for their lack of heart and ability to rise to the challenge in the final quarter, as well as focusing too much on their spearhead McKenna, while citing Carlton's evenness as the key to victory.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] The 44-point half-time deficit overcome by Carlton was then the second-largest half-time deficit ever overcome in VFL history.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] The only larger deficit overcome before this was 52 points, by Collingwood against St Kilda in Round 10 earlier in the season (which remains the record as of 2025).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] , speaking to a radio interview after the game.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] The game, and Barassi's half time instructions, are sometimes referred to as "the birth of modern football", a label which critical historical analysis views as symbolic, rather than literal.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Carlton's recovery in the 1970 grand final symbolized this transition perfectly: falling 44 points behind in the first half playing "old football", then recovering to win playing "new football" in the second half.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Nevertheless, the mythology surrounding the game has perpetuated a myth that Barassi's half-time instructions represented a revolutionary, seminal moment which heralded the transition from the old style of football to the modern style.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] This literal interpretation does not hold up to any critical assessment: Barassi noted that Carlton had been playing a handball style of game throughout 1970, and credited early 1960s Fitzroy coach Len Smith as being the first coach to encourage attacking use of handball in Victoria.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Football historian John Devaney assessed likewise that the transition towards handball and playing on had been gradual through the 1960s, and was already a well established tactic both within and outside Victoria in the years before 1970.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Barassi and Devaney both also note that Carlton's recovery couldn't be attributed to handball alone, with Hopkins strong play, better overall discipline and winning a higher proportion of possession also key to the recovery.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/1970-vfl-grand-final] Sports journalist Jake Niall, writing in 2020 as *The Age'*s chief football writer, argued that the 1970 Grand Final was "the most consequential match in the history of Australian rules football, the game that mattered most".
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/2024-afl-season-p01] The **2024 AFL season** was the 128th season of the Australian Football League (AFL), the highest-level senior men's Australian rules football competition in Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/2024-afl-season-p01] The season featured 18 clubs and ran from 7 March to 28 September, comprising a 23-match home-and-away season over 25 rounds, followed by a four-week finals series featuring the top eight clubs.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/2024-afl-season-p01] The Brisbane Lions won the premiership, defeating Sydney by 60 points in the 2024 AFL Grand Final; it was the Lions' fourth AFL premiership.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/2024-afl-season-p01] Sydney won the minor premiership by finishing atop the home-and-away ladder with a 17–6 win–loss record.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/2024-afl-season-p01] Carlton's Patrick Cripps won his second Brownlow Medal as the league's best and fairest player, breaking the record for most votes polled using the 3–2–1 voting system with 45, and Greater Western Sydney's Jesse Hogan won the Coleman Medal as the league's leading goalkicker.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/2024-afl-season-p01] In November 2023, the AFL and Seven Network announced that the usual start times for Thursday and Friday night matches would be brought forward by ten minutes to 7:30pm and 7:40pm (Melbourne time), respectively, for the upcoming season, in response to feedback from fans.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/2024-afl-season-p01] Andrew Dillon took over as CEO of the AFL from this season, commencing in October 2023.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/2024-afl-season-p01] Dillon replaced Gillon McLachlan, who had served in the role since 2014.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/2024-afl-season-p01] On 20 February 2024, goal umpire Jesse Baird was scheduled to officiate a practice match between Sydney and Greater Western Sydney, but did not arrive at the match.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/2024-afl-season-p01] One day later, New South Wales Police alleged Baird and his partner, Luke Davies, were murdered.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/2024-afl-season-p01] Before the start of the Sydney and Melbourne match, both teams formed a minute silence in the middle of the field, along with the umpires, in honoring Jesse Baird.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/2024-afl-season-p01] In an effort to grow the game in the northern states, the season featured an "Opening Round" wherein two matches in Sydney, one in Brisbane and one on the Gold Coast were played, prior to round 1.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/2024-afl-season-p01] Following its successful first iteration in 2023, Gather Round, a special round featuring all 18 clubs playing in the same region, was held for the second time in South Australia; it was held in round 4, from 4 to 7 April.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/2024-afl-season-p01] Following the season, several Greater Western Sydney players were sanctioned by the AFL for inappropriate costumes worn and skits performed at their Wacky Wednesday celebrations.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/2024-afl-season-p01] Captain Toby Greene was among seven players fined $5,000 for lack of leadership, Josh Fahey was suspended for four matches, and five other players were each suspended for two matches.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/2024-afl-season-p02] The following table includes all home match attendance figures from the home-and-away season, excluding neutral matches (Gather Round).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/2024-afl-season-p02] The following table can be sorted from biggest winning margin to biggest losing margin for each round.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/2024-afl-season-p02] If multiple matches in a round are decided by the same margin, these margins are sorted by percentage (i.e. the lowest-scoring winning team is ranked highest and the lowest-scoring losing team is ranked lowest).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/2024-afl-season-p02] Home matches are in bold, neutral matches (Gather Round) are underlined and opponents are listed above the margins.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/49th-parallel-cup] The **49th Parallel Cup** (formerly PanAm Cup) is an annual representative Australian rules football match between the United States and Canada first contested in 1999.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/49th-parallel-cup] Since 2007 the women's teams have also contested the cup.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/49th-parallel-cup] The men's matches are contested between the United States men's team ("The Revolution") and Canada's men's team ("The Northwind") while the women's matches are contested between the United States women's team ("The Freedom") and Canada's women's team ("The Northern Lights").
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/49th-parallel-cup] The cup is historically paused during the Australian Football International Cup year to enable the countries to compete at that tournament.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/49th-parallel-cup] Between 2015 and 2021 the cup went into recess for several reasons, primarily due to the 2017 Australian Football International Cup followed by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-asia-cup] The **AFL Asia Cup** is a triennial international tournament in Australian rules football.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-asia-cup] It is the biggest international tournament in the sport that is open to all nations in Asia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-asia-cup] It was created as a replacement of the AFL International Cup alongside the AFL Transatlantic Cup and the AFL Pacific Cup after the competition was affected by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-asia-cup] In August 2021, the AFL announced that the IC would return in 2023 to align with its original three-year schedule but did not announce the host.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-asia-cup] On 22 April 2022, the AFL announced it was postponing the International Cup until 2024 citing "significant investment required from the AFL to host the event".
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-asia-cup] However, on 24 July 2023, the AFL announced that, in lieu of the International Cup, that it would be sponsoring three regional events in 2024: the Trans-Atlantic Cup, the Asia Cup, and the Pacific Cup to be hosted by an international affiliate.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-asia-cup] The AFL gave no indication as to when the International Cup would be resumed, however indicated that these are the only AFL sanctioned international tournaments since 2017 (effectively nullifying the 2019 and 2022 AFL Europe Championship).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-asia-cup] AFL Canada was announced as host of the Transatlantic Cup to be held at the Humber College Oval at Colonel Samuel Smith Park in Toronto on August 2–11, The Maroochydore Multi Sports Complex on the Sunshine Coast, Queensland was announced as the host of the Pacific Cup on 14–24 November.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-asia-cup] Thanh Long Sports Center in Vietnam would host the Asia Cup at in Ho Chi Minh City from December 6–8 in 2024.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-asia-cup] The AFL announced strict selection criteria, that each player must hold citizenship for the country that they are representing and must have played in from a local competition in that country.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-asia-cup] The 2024 competition was contested by 10 teams in the men's division and 4 teams in the women's division.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-canberra-p01] The league was founded as the **Federal Territory Australian Rules Football League** in 1924 with founding members Acton and Queanbeyan.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-canberra-p01] The following year, the premiership was contested by 4 clubs including Canberra, Federal and Duntroon.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-canberra-p01] By 1926 the competition had gained popularity and was contested by 5 clubs.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-canberra-p01] In November 2010 the five AFL Canberra Premier Division clubs merged with the Premier Division clubs of the Queensland Australian Football League to form the North East Australian Football League.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-canberra-p01] From 2011 onwards, the AFL Canberra Premier Division together with the reserve sides from the Sydney Swans and Greater Western Sydney Giants would form the NEAFL Eastern Conference.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-canberra-p01] However the NEAFL was later dissolved due primarily to the COVID pandemic and associated financial pressures.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-canberra-p01] The AFL Canberra has been through a number of forms.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-canberra-p01] Clubs listed by highest grade of competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-canberra-p01] Point colours indicate club's highest level of competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The **AFL Commission** is the board of directors that governs the Australian Football League (AFL).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] Its chairman has been Richard Goyder since 4 April 2017.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] In 1985, the AFL (then named Victorian Football League Limited) formed the commission as a body independent of its member clubs, to operate its competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] In 1993, the independent commissioners took over from the AFL's board of directors, who had been representatives of its then-15 member clubs.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] In 1995, the AFL took over the operations of the Australian National Football Council which had published the Laws of Australian Football.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The AFL's constitution self-proclaims it to be the "keeper of the code" responsible for the sport of Australian football.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The AFL operates the All-Australian team, World (formerly All-international) team and Australian Football Hall of Fame.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The AFL operates the premier professional Australian Football competition in Australia and the State of Origin competition (1991-1999 and 2026-present).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] Since 1998, it has also overseen Australia's involvement in the International Rules Series.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] An independent governing body for the competition was first moved in December 1984 during the fallout of VFL president Allen Aylett's resignation following the South Melbourne Football Club's financially disastrous relocation to Sydney.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The club, managed from Melbourne but playing in Sydney, had sustained substantial finanical losses in Sydney and large loans had been written out by the league to keep them viable, which was also impacting the finances of the competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] Under its first chief commissioner, Jack Hamilton, the VFL began a restructuring toward a franchise model, whereby member clubs operate licenses owned by the league.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The model helped make private ownership of the Swans possible in 1985, as well as the sale of new licenses, resulting in the entry of the Brisbane Bears and West Coast Eagles in 1987.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] Under the new model, many Melbourne clubs struggling for financial viability such as St Kilda, Fitzroy and North Melbourne could be kept afloat by a combination of private ownership and league subsidies from the sale of new clubs and television rights.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The restructuring paved the way for the VFL's expansion into a national competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] Despite continuing financial troubles at many clubs, including the Swans and Footscray, the AFL was able to turn the competition's finances around by 1989, aided by increased television rights and the sale of $4 million licenses to interstate expansion clubs.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] In 2014, all AFL players were fully-paid professionals for the first time in the competition's history.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The AFL is governed by its board of directors, called the AFL Commission.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] In 1995, the AFL took over the operations of the Australian National Football Council, which ceased operations after 89 years of existence.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] In 2002, it took over the operations of the International Australian Football Council.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] In 2010, it took over the operations of Women's Football Australia, which ceased operations in 2015.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The AFL took over the operations of the New South Wales Australian Football League Limited, and the AFL subsidiary, AFL NSW/ACT now operates in Australia's most populous eastern state and the ACT.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The AFL promotes and brands the sport under its own name rather than of the formal name of Australian Football.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The ten commissioners are elected by the 18 AFL clubs, with each of the 18 clubs entitled to make nominations, but other Australian Football leagues, associations and clubs do not have any control or representation.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The AFL approves new club franchise licenses to expand its competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] Since 1987, it has been instrumental in the merger that created the Brisbane Lions, while the Sydney Swans were fully owned by the AFL, which retains a controlling interest and reversion rights in the event the Sydney Swans do not repay debts to the AFL.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The AFL also fully owns the Greater Western Sydney Giants.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] Other clubs to have an AFL appointed board include the Sydney Swans, the Gold Coast Suns, Adelaide Football Club and Port Adelaide Football Club.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The AFL operates a Competitive Balance Fund, which redistributes profits to the clubs most in need to help ensure that all of its member clubs are financially sustainable in the long-term.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The AFL is financially dependent on the success of its competitions with the majority of its funding coming from the AFL competition broadcasting rights.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The 2025-2031 rights will earn $4.5 billion, the most lucrative in Australian sporting history.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The AFL operates the Australian Football Hall of Fame, the AFL men's underage championships and AFL Women's underage championships.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] It is also responsible for senior State of Origin competition, which will return in 2026 after a 27-year hiatus.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The AFL is administered by its commission of company directors, which sets policy and has directed the VFL/AFL (known then as the VFL) as the game's most professional league since December 1985.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] In 1993, the independent commissioners took over as the directors of the AFL from its Board of Directors, which had been appointed as delegates of its then 15 member clubs.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The Board of Directors voted itself out of existence, and the AFL's then 15 member clubs also voted to abolish the old system of club appointment of directors and to adopt a new Memorandum and Articles of Association for the AFL.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] This was a significant change of power: between 1985 and 1993, the VFL/AFL had required explicit approval by a 75% vote of its member teams for major items such as further expansion, mergers, relocations, and major capital works.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] In 1995, the AFL took over the operations of the ANFC (see Principle 2 below).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The AFL also created an international policy in 2005 and took over the operations of the International Australian Football Council.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] Amateur and semi-professional Australian Football competitions across Australia are mostly self-sufficient from the AFL.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] These competitions, their clubs and teams often buy equipment and apparel that is AFL branded which provides revenue to the AFL.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] Some junior competitions pay to use the AFL proprietary Auskick program and junior clubs pay the AFL for give-away packs at AFL run promotions in their localities.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The AFL has established a pathway that features junior Academies and scholarships from representational level up to its member clubs.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The highest level is the AFL Academy, with academies for each state being managed by their respective AFL clubs and affiliated governing bodies.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] Between 2010 and 2021, the AFL spent between $6–38 million per annum (under 5% of total revenue) on game development grants globally (excluding a one-off COVID-19 Pandemic community football recovery package).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] With a new TV rights deal in 2022 and to help the game at the grassroots continue its recovery post COVID-19 pandemic, the AFL increased its community grants to $67 million.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The ten commissioners are nominated and elected by vote of the 18 AFL member clubs.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] A two-thirds majority of member clubs have the power to veto over commission decisions.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The commission elects its chairman and employs a chief executive officer to oversees the management and operations of the AFL.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] While the commission is responsible for directing AFL policy, it has, on occasions, become directly involved in on and off-field matters relating to AFL competitions, players, coaches and managers.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] Sometimes these interventions have been in controversial circumstances.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The AFL owns a stake in the Gold Coast and Greater Western Sydney clubs.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The AFL manages a special fund called the Competitive Balance Fund (CBF) since 2004 as a grant of up to $5 million per club to ensure that member clubs remain financially viable.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] The system was later changed to the Annual Special Distribution (ASD) of $6.3 million shared among all clubs, as well as allowing for grants and special concessions, such as payments, to ensure that the AFL member clubs remain viable in the short term.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] In 2006, the AFL approved a $2.1 million special financial assistance package for Carlton.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/afl-commission] In early 2009, it increased Melbourne's assistance from $250,000 to $1 million and made a $1 million grant to Port Adelaide.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/aflx] The AFL held two official Australian Football League (AFL) pre-season AFLX competitions featuring senior AFL clubs and players, in 2018 and 2019, but these were unpopular with spectators and did not return in 2020.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/aflx] The variation continues to be promoted by the AFL Commission as a participation sport in development regions and areas, and particularly where full-sized cricket grounds are not available.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/aflx] Since the COVID-19 pandemic, AFLX has been merged with AFL 9s and retained only the X brand, co-branding AFL 9s as Junior X, Youth X and Senior X and aligning it with the more widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/aflx] The rules of the game differed from standard Australian rules football in some significant ways.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/aflx] The game was played on a rectangular soccer-sized pitch, allowing matches to be hosted by stadiums that usually lacked the suitable field dimensions for Australian rules football.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/aflx] AFLX was first trialled at Arden Street Oval in January 2017.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/aflx] Two months later, it was trialed at was first trialled on a soccer pitch at Lakeside Stadium in a match between the Port Melbourne Football Club and Coburg Football Club.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/aflx] AFLX pre-season competition was launched by AFL chief executive officer Gillon McLachlan at Docklands Stadium on 6 February 2018.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/aflx] McLachlan said that AFLX would help promote football internationally.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/aflx] The 2018 competition attracted more than 40,000 fans to tournaments in Adelaide, Melbourne and Sydney.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/aflx] In Melbourne, TV ratings were reported as "modest" by AFL standards, with the three events drawing an average five-city metro audience of over 120,000 on Channel Seven's secondary channels.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/aflx] The AFL made several rule tweaks midway through the second season in attempt to make it higher scoring by inflating the scoring points for behinds from 1 to 2, goals from 6 to 12 and Super Goals from 10 to 20.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/aflx] Whitten Legends Game was also played under "EJX" (modified version of AFLX named after E J Whitten) at AAMI Park in Melbourne.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/aflx] It attracted just 6,000 spectators, the lowest in the series history.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/aflx] AFLX did not return as a senior AFL competition in 2020, as AFL had a greater focus on AFLW.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/aflx] Post the COVID-19 pandemic, the AFL increased the number of players to 9, effectively merging AFLX with AFL 9s and aligning with the widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/aflx] The reception to the two AFL pre-season competitions among fans and the media was mostly poor, with ABC Radio Grandstand journalist Richard Hinds being particularly savage in labelling it a "hollow, unappealing, pressure-free, atmosphere-deficient, oval-in-a-rectangle hole yawn-fest".
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/aflx] Con Stavros of RMIT's school of Economics, Finance and Marketing, expressed doubts about the potential of AFLX to export Australian rules football but acknowledged that using rectangular playing fields instead of the standard cricket ones would make such expansion easier.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] In Australia, Australian rules football is the most popular spectator sport and the second most participated code of football.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] Since originating in Victoria in 1858 and spreading elsewhere from 1866, it has been played continuously in every Australian state since 1903 plus the two major territories since 1916.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] In most states it is referred to simply as just **football** or **footy** however in New South Wales and Queensland it is promoted under the acronym AFL by the local development bodies.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] The sport is played by more than half a million Australians.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] Players participate at an organised level in various forms from Auskick (age 5) through to school-based, underage (up to age 19), open age, to Masters (35+) competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] The season runs in most states and territories during the cooler seasons in Australia (from March to September), avoiding clashes with cricket, with the exception being the northern part of the Northern Territory where the season runs during the wet season (October to March).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] The highest participation rates (players per capita) can be found in the Northern Territory (5%), South Australia (4.8%), Victoria (4.3%), Western Australia (4.2%), Tasmania (3.3%) and the Australian Capital Territory (2.4%).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] Unlike other football codes which are strongest in urban areas, Australian rules football has the highest participation in regional and remote areas.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] Nationally this rate is 5.7%, almost double that of any other code.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] It is also fast growing in New South Wales and in Queensland, though with participation rates there of 1.2% it is considered a minor sport, lagging behind soccer and rugby league in overall interest.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] These two states represent more than half of the Australian population and this dichotomy of football culture is referred to as the Barassi Line.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] Australian rules football holds the match attendance record of any football code in Victoria (121,696), South Australia (66,987), Tasmania (24,968) and the Northern Territory (17,500).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] The national professional competitions are the men's Australian Football League (AFL) and AFL Women's (AFLW).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] Nationally these are the most popular football competitions of any code, with millions of TV viewers across the country.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] The AFL governs the code nationally through the AFL Commission based in Melbourne.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] The AFL originated in Victoria and changed its name from Victorian Football League in 1990 after a successful program of national expansion and for these reasons the governing body is often seen by those from other states as having a strong Victorian bias.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] The AFL discontinued representative matches as it expanded nationally (with the exception of occasional matches featuring Victoria).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] This was part of restructuring competitions across the country into a national junior pathway that would provide the league with access to the best junior talent via the Australian Football League draft.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] South Australia and Western Australia are the only states represented at the AFL Under 19 Championships, state representation is limited to players under 19, and open age players can only represent their state through interleague matches involving lower tier competitions.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] The Australian Football Hall of Fame names the greatest players of all time.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] Of the greatest 32 who are categorised as Legends: 20 are Victorian, 4 each are from South Australia and Tasmania, 3 from Western Australia, 2 from New South Wales and 1 each from Queensland and the Australian Capital Territory.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] Australia competed internationally at junior level.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] Australia's national teams remain undefeated.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] From 2007 to 2019 the underage men's team competed annually against international opponents as the AFL Academy most recently against New Zealand.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] Australia has also fielded amateur teams against South Africa, Papua New Guinea and the United States.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] Sides representing Indigenous Australia have competed against Papua New Guinea and South Africa.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] It began in the Colony of Victoria in 1858, followed by the Colony of New South Wales and Colony of Queensland (1866); Colony of South Australia (1877); Colony of Tasmania (1879); and, Colony of Western Australia (1881).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] The first intercolonial representative match was Victoria vs South Australia (1879).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] Delegates representing the football associations of South Australia, Tasmania, Victoria and Queensland met in 1883 in order to standardise the rules across the colonies.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] The earliest governing body, the Australasian Football Council (later Australian National Football Council) dates back to this time.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] Following a hiatus in Queensland (1892-1903) and New South Wales (1893-1903) it was revived after the Federation of Australia and expanded to the territories of the Australian Capital Territory (1911) and the Northern Territory (1916).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] The sport has had a significant impact on popular culture in its native Australia, capturing the imagination of Australian film, art, music, television and literature.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] Football is the most highly attended spectator sport in Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] Government figures show that more than 2.5 million people (16.8% of the population) attended games in 1999.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] In 2005, a cumulative 6,283,788 people attended Australian Football League (AFL) premiership matches, a record for the competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] A further 307,181 attended NAB Cup pre-season matches and 117,552 attended Regional Challenge pre-season practice matches around the country.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] As of 2010, the AFL is one of only five professional sports leagues with an average attendance of over 30,000 per game.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] As well as the AFL attendances, strong semi-professional state and local competitions also draw crowds.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] The South Australian SANFL drew an attendance in 2008 of 362,209 with an average of 3,773 per game, while the Western Australian WAFL drew an attendance of 219,205 with an average of 2,332 per game.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] According to OzTAM, in recent years, the AFL Grand Final has reached the top five programs across the five biggest cities in 2002, 2003, 2004, 2005 and 2006.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] Australian rules football has achieved a #1 rating in the sports category in both 2004 and 2005.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] The most powerful organisation and competition within the game is the elite professional Australian Football League (AFL).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] The AFL is recognised by the Australian Sports Commission as being the National Sporting Organisation for Australian rules football.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] There are also seven state/territory-based organisations in Australia, most of which are affiliated to the AFL.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] Most of these hold annual semi-professional club competitions while the others oversee more than one league.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] Local semi-professional or amateur organisations and competitions are affiliated to their state leagues.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] The last senior national carnival was held in 1993 and the last match between interstate senior sides was held under State of Origin rules in 1999.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] Senior state representation for Australian Football League players is no longer available except for Victoria whose players sometimes compete in one-off events against composite sides.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] However, state leagues continue to compete in inter-league matches.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] The **AFL Under 18 Championships** are the annual national Australian rules football championships for players aged 18 years or younger and includes teams from each Australian state or Territory.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] The competition is monitored by AFL recruiters and frequently seen as the second biggest pathway for junior players to the fully professional Australian Football League.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] The competition is currently sponsored by the National Australia Bank (NAB).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] The competition receives an increasing amount of coverage in the media, however still lags behind the TAC Cup in terms of interest in Victoria.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-australia/australian-rules-football-in-australia] AFL player states of origin based on junior participation.
